      "name": "LinearLayout",
      "category": "Encoding System (Thesis Core)",
      "spec_file": "docs/spec/linear-layout.md",
      "chapter": "ch.08",
      "blurb": "`LinearLayout` GF(2) algebra — the mathematical spine",
      "maturity": "L3",
      "reference_source": [
        "include/triton/Tools/LinearLayout.h",
        "lib/Tools/LinearLayout.cpp"
      ],
      "motivation": "Every TTGIR tensor carries an encoding attribute (`#ttg.blocked`, `#ttg.nvidia_mma`, `#ttg.dot_op`, `#ttg.swizzled_shared`) that describes how tensor elements are distributed across GPU hardware coordinates `{register, lane, warp, block}`. Without a **unified mathematical representation**, each encoding would need bespoke code for every optimization: coalescing, conversion removal, MMA selection, and swizzling. `LinearLayout` provides that unification — all encodings reduce to a single GF(2) linear function, and all optimizations become algebraic operations on that function.",
      "reference_chapter": "ch.08.LinearLayout",
      "textbook": "book-zh/ch.08.LinearLayout.md"
    },
    {
      "name": "BlockedEncoding",
      "category": "Encoding System (Thesis Core)",
      "spec_file": "docs/spec/blocked-encoding.md",
      "chapter": "ch.09",
      "blurb": "`BlockedEncoding` → `LinearLayout` via `identityStandardND`",
      "maturity": "L3",
      "reference_source": [
        "lib/Dialect/TritonGPU/IR/LinearLayoutConversions.cpp:889–897"
      ],
      "motivation": "`BlockedEncoding` is the default encoding assigned by `ConvertTritonToTritonGPU` (ch.06). It divides a tensor into rectangular tiles, each owned by one thread. The four parameters (`sizePerThread`, `threadsPerWarp`, `warpsPerCTA`, `order`) fully determine which thread owns which element. Converting these parameters to a `LinearLayout` enables all downstream optimizations to work uniformly — they query `getNumConsecutiveInOut()`, `sublayout()`, and `invertAndCompose()` without knowing the encoding type.",
      "reference_chapter": "ch.09.BlockedEncoding",
      "textbook": "book-zh/ch.09.BlockedEncoding.md"
    },
    {
      "name": "NvidiaMmaEncoding",
      "category": "Encoding System (Thesis Core)",
      "spec_file": "docs/spec/mma-encoding.md",
      "chapter": "ch.10",
      "blurb": "`NvidiaMmaEncoding` + `DotOperandEncoding` fragment mapping",
      "maturity": "L3",
      "reference_source": [
        "lib/Dialect/TritonGPU/IR/LinearLayoutConversions.cpp:940–1054"
      ],
      "motivation": "`NvidiaMmaEncoding` describes the layout of the result tensor from a `mma.sync.aligned.m16n8k16` instruction. Each of the 32 lanes in a warp holds specific fragments of the 16×8 result tile. `DotOperandEncoding` describes the layout of the input operands (A and B) that feed into the MMA instruction. It must match the hardware's expected fragment distribution for `ldmatrix` + `mma.sync` to work correctly.",
      "reference_chapter": "ch.10.MMA-DotOperand-Encoding",
      "textbook": "book-zh/ch.10.MMA-DotOperand-Encoding.md"
    },
    {
      "name": "SwizzledSharedEncoding",
      "category": "Encoding System (Thesis Core)",
      "spec_file": "docs/spec/swizzled-shared-encoding.md",
      "chapter": "ch.11",
      "blurb": "`SwizzledSharedEncoding` XOR bank-conflict elimination",
      "maturity": "L3",
      "reference_source": [
        "lib/Dialect/TritonGPU/IR/LinearLayoutConversions.cpp:49–113"
      ],
      "motivation": "Shared memory on NVIDIA GPUs has 32 banks. When multiple threads in a warp access the same bank simultaneously (but different addresses within that bank), the accesses are serialized — a **bank conflict**. `SwizzledSharedEncoding` eliminates bank conflicts by XOR-ing the column address with a row-dependent phase:",
      "reference_chapter": "ch.11.SwizzledShared-Encoding",
      "textbook": "book-zh/ch.11.SwizzledShared-Encoding.md"
    },
    {
      "name": "ttgir-encoding-interfaces",
      "category": "Encoding System (Thesis Core)",
      "spec_file": "docs/spec/ttgir-encoding-interfaces.md",
      "chapter": "ch.05",
      "blurb": "Encoding attribute inventory and interface contract",
      "maturity": "L2",
      "motivation": "TTGIR encoding attributes describe how tensor elements are distributed across GPU threads. Each encoding can be reduced to a `LinearLayout` — a GF(2) linear function mapping `{register, lane, warp, block}` to tensor coordinates.",
      "reference_chapter": "ch.05.TTGIR-Dialect",
      "textbook": "book-zh/ch.05.TTGIR-Dialect.md"
    },
    {
      "name": "CoalescePass",
      "category": "Optimization Passes (Thesis Core)",
      "spec_file": "docs/spec/coalesce-pass.md",
      "chapter": "ch.12",
      "blurb": "`CoalescePass` — vectorized memory access (T3a)",
      "maturity": "L3",
      "reference_source": [
        "lib/Dialect/TritonGPU/Transforms/Coalesce.cpp"
      ],
      "motivation": "After `ConvertTritonToTritonGPU` (ch.06), all tensors have `sizePerThread={1,...}` — each thread handles one element at a time. This wastes memory bandwidth: NVIDIA GPUs can load 4–8 elements per thread in a single vectorized instruction. CoalescePass analyzes pointer contiguity and increases `sizePerThread` to enable vectorized loads/stores.",
      "reference_chapter": "ch.12.CoalescePass",
      "textbook": "book-zh/ch.12.CoalescePass.md"
    },
    {
      "name": "RemoveLayoutConversions",
      "category": "Optimization Passes (Thesis Core)",
      "spec_file": "docs/spec/layout-propagation.md",
      "chapter": "ch.13",
      "blurb": "`RemoveLayoutConversions` 4-phase algorithm (T3b)",
      "maturity": "L3",
      "reference_source": [
        "lib/Dialect/TritonGPU/Transforms/RemoveLayoutConversions.cpp"
      ],
      "motivation": "Eliminate unnecessary `ttg.convert_layout` operations by propagating encodings through **encoding-agnostic** ops (arith, splat, broadcast, etc.). This is thesis **T3b**: without layout-conversion removal, the pipeline would insert O(n) convert_layout ops between every pair of differently-encoded ops, each requiring a full shared-memory round-trip.",
      "reference_chapter": "ch.13.LayoutPropagation",
      "textbook": "book-zh/ch.13.LayoutPropagation.md"
    },
    {
      "name": "LayoutRematerialization",
      "category": "Optimization Passes (Thesis Core)",
      "spec_file": "docs/spec/layout-rematerialization.md",
